695. omnis homines is a large-sounding phrase, but very much easier for Pampilus to say than the definite patrem which the occasion really demands.

696. contigit is impersonal; translate “I won her.’' — valeant properly means “ good health to those.'' The use of the second person as a formula of leave taking, “ farewell ! '’ is, however, often extended to the third person. Translate “ good-by to those.”

697. nemo, instead of nihil, shows that Pampilus has a definite individua! in mind.
